# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: faker-data
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] In the context of medical data, anonymized data refers to data from which the patient cannot be identified by the recipient of the information.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] The name, address, and full postcode must be removed, together with any other information which, in conjunction with other data held by or disclosed to the recipient, could identify the patient.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] There will always be a risk that anonymized data may not stay anonymous over time.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] Pairing the anonymized dataset with other data, clever techniques and raw power are some of the ways previously anonymous data sets have become de-anonymized; The data subjects are no longer anonymous.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] De-anonymization is the reverse process in which anonymous data is cross-referenced with other data sources to re-identify the anonymous data source.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] Generalization and perturbation are the two popular anonymization approaches for relational data.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] The process of obscuring data with the ability to re-identify it later is also called pseudonymization and is one way companies can store data in a way that is HIPAA compliant.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] However, according to ARTICLE 29 DATA PROTECTION WORKING PARTY, Directive 95/46/EC refers to anonymisation in Recital 26 "signifies that to anonymise any data, the data must be stripped of sufficient elements such that the data subject can no longer be identified.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] More precisely, that data must be processed in such a way that it can no longer be used to identify a natural person by using “all the means likely reasonably to be used” by either the controller or a third party.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] An important factor is that the processing must be irreversible.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] The Directive does not clarify how such a de-identification process should or could be performed.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] The focus is on the outcome: that data should be such as not to allow the data subject to be identified via “all” “likely” and “reasonable” means.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] Reference is made to codes of conduct as a tool to set out possible anonymisation mechanisms as well as retention in a form in which identification of the data subject is “no longer possible”.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] There are five types of data anonymization operations: generalization, suppression, anatomization, permutation, and perturbation.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) requires that stored data on people in the EU undergo either anonymization or a pseudonymization process.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] According to the EDPS and AEPD, no one, including the data controller, should be able to re-identify data subjects in a properly anonymized dataset.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] Research by data scientists at Imperial College in London and UCLouvain in Belgium, as well as a ruling by Judge Michal Agmon-Gonen of the Tel Aviv District Court, highlight the shortcomings of "Anonymisation" in today's big data world.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] Anonymisation reflects an outdated approach to data protection that was developed when the processing of data was limited to isolated (siloed) applications, prior to the popularity of big data processing involving the widespread sharing and combining of data.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] Removing identifying metadata from computer files is important for anonymizing them.
[src:faker-data/data-anonymization] Metadata removal tools are useful for achieving this.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Faker is heavily inspired by PHP Faker, Perl Faker, and by Ruby Faker.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Starting from version `4.0.0`, `Faker` dropped support for Python 2 and from version `5.0.0` only supports Python 3.8 and above.
[src:faker-data/index-page] If you still need Python 2 compatibility, please install version `3.0.1` in the meantime, and please consider updating your codebase to support Python 3 so you can enjoy the latest features `Faker` has to offer.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Please see the extended docs for more details, especially if you are upgrading from version `2.0.4` and below as there might be breaking changes.
[src:faker-data/index-page] This package was also previously called `fake-factory` which was already deprecated by the end of 2016, and much has changed since then, so please ensure that your project and its dependencies do not depend on the old package.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Use `faker.Faker()` to create and initialize a faker generator, which can generate data by accessing properties named after the type of data you want.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Each call to method `fake.name()` yields a different (random) result.
[src:faker-data/index-page] This is because faker forwards `faker.Generator.method_name()` calls to `faker.Generator.format(method_name)`.
[src:faker-data/index-page] `Faker` also has its own `pytest` plugin which provides a `faker` fixture you can use in your tests.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Please check out the *pytest fixture docs* to learn more.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Each of the generator properties (like `name`, `address`, and `lorem`) are called “fake”.
[src:faker-data/index-page] A faker generator has many of them, packaged in “providers”.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Check the extended docs for a list of bundled providers and a list of community providers.
[src:faker-data/index-page] `faker.Faker` can take a locale as an argument, to return localized data.
[src:faker-data/index-page] If no localized provider is found, the factory falls back to the default LCID string for US english, ie: `en_US`.
[src:faker-data/index-page] `faker.Faker` also supports multiple locales.
[src:faker-data/index-page] You can check available Faker locales in the source code, under the providers package.
[src:faker-data/index-page] The localization of Faker is an ongoing process, for which we need your help.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Please don’t hesitate to create a localized provider for your own locale and submit a Pull Request (PR).
[src:faker-data/index-page] The Faker constructor takes a performance-related argument called `use_weighting`.
[src:faker-data/index-page] It specifies whether to attempt to have the frequency of values match real-world frequencies (e.g. the English name Gary would be much more frequent than the name Lorimer).
[src:faker-data/index-page] If `use_weighting` is `False`, then all items have an equal chance of being selected, and the selection process is much faster.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Dynamic providers can read elements from an external source.
[src:faker-data/index-page] You can provide your own sets of words if you don’t want to use the default lorem ipsum one.
[src:faker-data/index-page] By default all generators share the same instance of `random.Random`, which can be accessed with `from faker.generator import random`.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Using this may be useful for plugins that want to affect all faker instances.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Through use of the `.unique` property on the generator, you can guarantee that any generated values are unique for this specific instance.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Calling `fake.unique.clear()` clears the already seen values.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Note, to avoid infinite loops, after a number of attempts to find a unique value, Faker will throw a `UniquenessException`.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Beware of the birthday paradox, collisions are more likely than you’d think.
[src:faker-data/index-page] In addition, only hashable arguments and return values can be used with `.unique`.
[src:faker-data/index-page] When using Faker for unit testing, you will often want to generate the same data set.
[src:faker-data/index-page] For convenience, the generator also provides a `seed()` method, which seeds the shared random number generator.
[src:faker-data/index-page] A Seed produces the same result when the same methods with the same version of faker are called.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Each generator can also be switched to use its own instance of `random.Random`, separated from the shared one, by using the `seed_instance()` method, which acts the same way.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Please note that as we keep updating datasets, results are not guaranteed to be consistent across patch versions.
[src:faker-data/index-page] If you hardcode results in your test, make sure you pinned the version of `Faker` down to the patch number.
[src:faker-data/index-page] If you are using `pytest`, you can seed the `faker` fixture by defining a `faker_seed` fixture.
[src:faker-data/index-page] Faker is released under the MIT License.
[src:faker-data/index-page] See the bundled LICENSE file for details.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The abbreviation PII is widely used in the United States, but the phrase it abbreviates has four common variants based on *personal* or *personally*, and *identifiable* or *identifying*.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Not all are equivalent, and for legal purposes the effective definitions vary depending on the jurisdiction and the purposes for which the term is being used.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Under European Union and United Kingdom data protection regimes, which centre primarily on the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), the term "personal data" is significantly broader, and determines the scope of the regulatory regime.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Personal data is defined under the GDPR as "any information which [is] related to an identified or identifiable natural person".
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The IP address of an Internet subscriber may be classed as personal data.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The concept of PII has become prevalent as information technology and the Internet have made it easier to collect PII leading to a profitable market in collecting and reselling PII.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] PII can also be exploited by criminals to stalk or steal the identity of a person, or to aid in the planning of criminal acts.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] As a response to these threats, many website privacy policies specifically address the gathering of PII, and lawmakers such as the European Parliament have enacted a series of legislative acts such as the GDPR to limit the distribution and accessibility of PII.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Serious confusion arises around whether PII means information which is identifiable (that is, can be associated with a person) or identifying (that is, associated uniquely with a person, such that the PII *identifies* them).
[src:faker-data/personal-data] In prescriptive data privacy regimes such as the US federal Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA), PII items have been specifically defined.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] In broader data protection regimes such as the GDPR, personal data is defined in a non-prescriptive principles-based way.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Information that might not count as PII under HIPAA can be personal data for the purposes of GDPR.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] For this reason, "PII" is typically deprecated internationally.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] In the EU rules, there has been a more specific notion that the data subject can potentially be identified through additional processing of other attributes—quasi- or pseudo-identifiers.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] A simple example of this distinction: the color name "red" by itself is *not* personal data, but that same value stored as part of a person's record as their "favorite color" *is* personal data; it is the connection to the person that makes it personal data, not (as in PII) the value itself.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The concept of information combination given in the SB1386 definition is key to correctly distinguishing PII, as defined by OMB, from "personal information", as defined by SB1386.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Information, such as a name, that lacks context cannot be said to be SB1386 "personal information", but it must be said to be PII as defined by OMB.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] For example, the name "John Smith" has no meaning in the current context and is therefore not SB1386 "personal information", but it is PII.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] A Social Security Number (SSN) without a name or some other associated identity or context information is not SB1386 "personal information", but it is PII.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] For example, the SSN 078-05-1120 by itself is PII, but it is not SB1386 "personal information".
[src:faker-data/personal-data] However the combination of a valid name with the correct SSN is SB1386 "personal information".
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The combination of a name with a context may also be considered PII; for example, if a person's name is on a list of patients for an HIV clinic.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] However, it is not necessary for the name to be combined with a context in order for it to be PII.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The reason for this distinction is that bits of information such as names, although they may not be sufficient by themselves to make an identification, may later be combined with other information to identify persons and expose them to harm.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The scope of the term "sensitive personal data" varies by jurisdiction.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] In the UK, personal health data is treated as "sensitive" and in need of additional data protection measures.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] According to the OMB, in the United States it is not always the case that PII is "sensitive", and context may be taken into account in deciding whether certain PII is or is not sensitive.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] When a person wishes to remain anonymous, descriptions of them will often employ several of the above, such as "a 34-year-old white male who works at Target".
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Information can still be *private*, in the sense that a person may not wish for it to become publicly known, without being personally identifiable.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Moreover, sometimes multiple pieces of information, none sufficient by itself to uniquely identify an individual, may uniquely identify a person when combined; this is one reason that multiple pieces of evidence are usually presented at criminal trials.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] It has been shown that, in 1990, 87% of the population of the United States could be uniquely identified by gender, ZIP code, and full date of birth.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] In hacker and Internet slang, the practice of finding and releasing such information is called "doxing".
[src:faker-data/personal-data] It is sometimes used to deter collaboration with law enforcement.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] On occasion, the doxing can trigger an arrest, particularly if law enforcement agencies suspect that the "doxed" individual may panic and disappear.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] It appears that this definition is significantly broader than the Californian example given above, and thus that Australian privacy law may cover a broader category of data and information than in some US law.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The term "PII" is not used in Australian privacy law.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] European Union data protection law does not use the concept of personally identifiable information, and its scope is instead determined by the non-synonymous, wider concept of "personal data".
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Further examples can be found on the EU privacy website.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] On 1 June 2023, the Hong Kong Office of the Privacy Commissioner for Personal Data published an investigation report on a data breach involving the unauthorised access of a credit reference database platform.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The Report highlights the need for organizations to take adequate steps to protect personal data as the mere imposition of contractual obligations and policies is insufficient if such obligations and policies are not effective or are not enforced.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The Report also clarifies that credit data is a form of "sensitive" personal data.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The twelve Information Privacy Principles of the Privacy Act 1993 apply.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] New Zealand enacted the Privacy Act in 2020 to promote and protect individual privacy.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The Federal Act on Data Protection of 19 June 1992 (in force since 1993) has set up a protection of privacy by prohibiting virtually any processing of personal data which is not expressly authorized by the data subjects.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The protection is subject to the authority of the Federal Data Protection and Information Commissioner.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Additionally, any person may ask in writing a company managing data files to correct or delete any personal data.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The company must respond within thirty days.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] One of the primary focuses of the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) is to protect a patient's Protected Health Information (PHI), which is similar to PII.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Senate proposed the Privacy Act of 2005, which attempted to strictly limit the display, purchase, or sale of PII without the person's consent.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Similarly, the (proposed) Anti-Phishing Act of 2005 attempted to prevent the acquiring of PII through phishing.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] U.S. lawmakers have paid special attention to the social security number because it can be easily used to commit identity theft.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The (proposed) Social Security Number Protection Act of 2005 and (proposed) Identity Theft Prevention Act of 2005 each sought to limit the distribution of an individual's social security number.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Additional U.S.-specific personally identifiable information includes, but is not limited to, I-94 records, Medicaid ID numbers, and Internal Revenue Service (I.R.S.) documentation.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Exclusivity of personally identifiable information affiliated with the U.S. highlights national data security concerns and the influence of personally identifiable information in U.S. federal data management systems.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) is a physical sciences laboratory, and a non-regulatory agency of the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Its mission is to promote innovation and industrial competitiveness.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The following are less often used to distinguish individual identity, because they are traits shared by many people.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] However, they are potentially PII, because they may be combined with other personal information to identify an individual.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] In forensics, particularly the identification and prosecution of criminals, personally identifiable information is critical in establishing evidence in criminal procedure.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Personal data is a key component of online identity and can be exploited by individuals.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] For instance, data can be altered and used to create fake documents, hijack mail boxes and phone calls or harass people, as occurred in 2019 to a customer of the EE mobile phone operator in the UK.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Another category can be referred to as financial identity theft, which usually entails bank account and credit card information being stolen, and then being used or sold.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Personal data can also be used to create fake online identities, including fake accounts and profiles (which can be referred as identity cloning or identity fraud) for celebrities to gather data from other users more easily.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Even individuals can be concerned, especially for personal purposes (this is more widely known as sockpuppetry).
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The most critical information, such as one's password, date of birth, ID documents or social security number, can be used to log in to different websites (e.g. password reuse and account verification) to gather more information and access more content.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Also, several agencies ask for discretion on subjects related to their work, for the safety of their employees.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] For this reason, the United States Department of Defense (DoD) has strict policies controlling release of personally identifiable information of DoD personnel.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Many intelligence agencies have similar policies, sometimes to the point where employees do not disclose to their friends that they work for the agency.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Similar identity protection concerns exist for witness protection programs, women's shelters, and victims of domestic violence and other threats.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Personal information removal services work by identifying and requesting data brokers to delete the personal information of their clients.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] This process can be manual or fully automated, but it is nevertheless complex because it involves dealing with numerous data brokers, each with different policies and procedures for data removal.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Companies offering personal information removal also face some issues.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] They struggle to ensure comprehensive data removal as new data brokers emerge and existing ones don’t always comply with removal requests.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Most of them are also limited to certain regions or countries.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] During the second half of the 20th century, the digital revolution introduced "privacy economics", or the trade of personal data.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The value of data can change over time and over different contexts.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Disclosing data can reverse information asymmetry, though the costs of doing so can be unclear.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] In relation to companies, consumers often have "imperfect information regarding when their data is collected, with what purposes, and with what consequences".
[src:faker-data/personal-data] In the mid-1990s, Varian retook the Chicago Boys approach and added a new externality, stating that the consumer would not always have perfect information on how their own data would be used.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Laudon developed a model in which individuals own their data and have the ability to sell it as a product.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] He believed that such a system should not be regulated, to create a free market.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] In the 2000s, researchers worked on price discrimination (Taylor, 2004), two-sided markets (Cornière, 2011) and marketing strategies (Anderson and de Palma, 2012).
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The theories became complex, and showed that the impact of privacy on the economy highly depended on the context.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Sources, usually Internet-based since the 1990s, may include census and electoral roll records, social networking sites, court reports and purchase histories.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] The information from data brokers may be used in background checks used by employers and housing.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] There are varying regulations around the world limiting the collection of information on individuals; privacy laws vary.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] In the United States there is no federal regulation protection for the consumer from data brokers, although some states have begun enacting laws individually.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] In the European Union, GDPR serves to regulate data brokers' operations.
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Some data brokers report to have large numbers of population data or "data attributes".
[src:faker-data/personal-data] Acxiom purports to have data from 2.5 billion different people.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] A **pseudorandom** sequence of numbers is one that appears to be statistically random, despite having been produced by a completely deterministic and repeatable process.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] The generation of random numbers has many uses, such as for random sampling, Monte Carlo methods, board games, or gambling.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] In physics, however, most processes, such as gravitational acceleration, are deterministic, meaning that they always produce the same outcome from the same starting point.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] Some notable exceptions are radioactive decay and quantum measurement, which are both modeled as being truly random processes in the underlying physics.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] Since these processes are not practical sources of random numbers, pseudorandom numbers are used, which ideally have the unpredictability of a truly random sequence, despite being generated by a deterministic process.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] In many applications, the deterministic process is a computer algorithm called a pseudorandom number generator, which must first be provided with a number called a random seed.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] Since the same seed will yield the same sequence every time, it is important that the seed be well chosen and kept hidden, especially in security applications, where the pattern's unpredictability is a critical feature.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] In some cases where it is important for the sequence to be demonstrably unpredictable, physical sources of random numbers have been used, such as radioactive decay, atmospheric electromagnetic noise harvested from a radio tuned between stations, or intermixed timings of keystrokes.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] The time investment needed to obtain these numbers leads to a compromise: using some of these physics readings as a seed for a pseudorandom number generator.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] Before modern computing, researchers requiring random numbers would either generate them through various means (dice, cards, roulette wheels, etc.) or use existing random number tables.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] The first attempt to provide researchers with a ready supply of random digits was in 1927, when the Cambridge University Press published a table of 41,600 digits developed by L.H.C.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] In 1947, the RAND Corporation generated numbers by the electronic simulation of a roulette wheel; the results were eventually published in 1955 as *A Million Random Digits with 100,000 Normal Deviates*.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] In theoretical computer science, a distribution is **pseudorandom** against a class of adversaries if no adversary from the class can distinguish it from the uniform distribution with significant advantage.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] This notion of pseudorandomness is studied in computational complexity theory and has applications to cryptography.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] Formally, let *S* and *T* be finite sets and let **F** = {*f*: *S* → *T*} be a class of functions.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] A distribution **D** over *S* is ε-**pseudorandom** against **F** if for every *f* in **F**, the statistical distance between the distributions $f(X)$ and $f(Y)$ , where X is sampled from **D** and Y is sampled from the uniform distribution on *S*, is at most ε.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] In typical applications, the class **F** describes a model of computation with bounded resources and one is interested in designing distributions **D** with certain properties that are pseudorandom against **F**.
[src:faker-data/pseudorandomness] The distribution **D** is often specified as the output of a pseudorandom generator.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Data generated by a computer simulation can be seen as synthetic data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] This encompasses most applications of physical modeling, such as music synthesizers or flight simulators.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] The output of such systems approximates the real thing, but is fully algorithmically generated.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Synthetic data is used in a variety of fields as a filter for information that would otherwise compromise the confidentiality of particular aspects of the data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] In many sensitive applications, datasets theoretically exist but cannot be released to the general public; synthetic data sidesteps the privacy issues that arise from using real consumer information without permission or compensation.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Synthetic data is generated to meet specific needs or certain conditions that may not be found in the original, real data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] One of the hurdles in applying up-to-date machine learning approaches for complex scientific tasks is the scarcity of labeled data, a gap effectively bridged by the use of synthetic data, which closely replicates real experimental data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] This can be useful when designing many systems, from simulations based on theoretical value, to database processors, etc.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] This helps detect and solve unexpected issues such as information processing limitations.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Synthetic data are often generated to represent the authentic data and allows a baseline to be set.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Another benefit of synthetic data is to protect the privacy and confidentiality of authentic data, while still allowing for use in testing systems.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Computer security experts claim generated synthetic data "... enables us to create realistic behavior profiles for users and attackers.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] At the same time, synthetic data together with the testing approach can give the ability to model real-world scenarios.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Scientific modelling of physical systems has a long history that runs concurrent with the history of physics.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] For example, research into synthesis of audio and voice can be traced back to the 1930s and before, driven forward by the developments of the telephone and audio recording technologies.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Digitization gave rise to software synthesizers from the 1970s onwards.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] In the context of privacy-preserving statistical analysis, in 1993, the idea of original fully synthetic data was created by Donald Rubin.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Rubin originally designed this to synthesize the Decennial Census long form responses for the short form households.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] He then released samples that did not include any actual long form records - in this he preserved anonymity of the household.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Later that year, the idea of original partially synthetic data was created by Little.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Little used this idea to synthesize the sensitive values on the public use file.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] A 1993 work fitted a statistical model to 60,000 MNIST digits, then it was used to generate over 1 million examples.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Those were used to train a LeNet-4 to reach state of the art performance.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] In 1994, Stephen Fienberg introduced 'critical refinement', in which a parametric posterior predictive distribution (instead of a Bayes bootstrap) is used to do the sampling.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Later, other important contributors to the development of synthetic data generation were Trivellore Raghunathan, Jerry Reiter, Donald Rubin, John M.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Collectively they came up with a solution for how to treat partially synthetic data with missing data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Similarly, they developed the technique of Sequential Regression Multivariate Imputation.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Researchers test the framework on synthetic data, which is "the only source of ground truth on which they can objectively assess the performance of their algorithms".
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Synthetic data can be generated through the use of random lines, having different orientations and starting positions.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] A more complicated dataset can be generated by using a synthesizer build.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] To create a synthesizer build, first use the original data to create a model or equation that fits the data the best.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] This model or equation will be called a synthesizer build.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] This build can be used to generate more data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Constructing a synthesizer build involves constructing a statistical model.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] In a linear regression line example, the original data can be plotted, and a best fit linear line can be created from the data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] This line is a synthesizer created from the original data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] The next step will be generating more synthetic data from the synthesizer build or from this linear line equation.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] In this way, the new data can be used for studies and research, and it protects the confidentiality of the original data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Generate attribute values based on user-supplied prior probabilities.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Since the attribute values of one object may depend on the attribute values of related objects, the attribute generation process assigns values collectively.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Testing and training fraud detection and confidentiality systems are devised using synthetic data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Specific algorithms and generators are designed to create realistic data, which then assists in teaching a system how to react to certain situations or criteria.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] For example, intrusion detection software is tested using synthetic data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] This data is a representation of the authentic data and may include intrusion instances that are not found in the authentic data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] The synthetic data allows the software to recognize these situations and react accordingly.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] If synthetic data was not used, the software would only be trained to react to the situations provided by the authentic data and it may not recognize another type of intrusion.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Researchers doing clinical trials or any other research may generate synthetic data to aid in creating a baseline for future studies and testing.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Real data can contain information that researchers may not want released, so synthetic data is sometimes used to protect the privacy and confidentiality of a dataset.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Using synthetic data reduces confidentiality and privacy issues since it holds no personal information and cannot be traced back to any individual.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Beyond privacy protection, synthetic data is also being explored for methodological innovation in drug development.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] For instance, synthetic data may be used to construct synthetic control arms as an alternative to conventional external control arms based on real-world data (RWD) or randomized controlled trials (RCTs).
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Collectively, regulatory agencies such as the FDA and EMA appear to be at various stages of recognizing and integrating AI-generated synthetic data into their methodologies.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] The quality and statistical handling of synthetic data are expected to become more prominent in future regulatory discussions, particularly in contexts such as predictive modeling (e.g., digital twins), where innovative approaches have already been referenced.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Synthetic data is increasingly being used for machine learning applications: a model is trained on a synthetically generated dataset with the intention of transfer learning to real data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Efforts have been made to enable more data science experiments via the construction of general-purpose synthetic data generators, such as the Synthetic Data Vault.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] This usage of synthetic data has been proposed for computer vision applications, in particular object detection, where the synthetic environment is a 3D model of the object, and learning to navigate environments by visual information.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] In the context of large language model training, synthetic data generation has become a core component of the post-training pipeline.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] At the same time, transfer learning remains a nontrivial problem, and synthetic data has not become ubiquitous yet.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Research results indicate that adding a small amount of real data significantly improves transfer learning with synthetic data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Advances in generative adversarial networks (GAN), lead to the natural idea that one can produce data and then use it for training.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] Since at least 2016, such adversarial training has been successfully used to produce synthetic data of sufficient quality to produce state-of-the-art results in some domains, without even needing to re-mix real data in with the generated synthetic data.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] In 1987, a Navlab autonomous vehicle used 1200 synthetic road images as one approach to training.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] In 2021, Microsoft released a database of 100,000 synthetic faces based on (500 real faces) that claims to "match real data in accuracy".
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] In 2023, Nature (journal) published a cover of their Nature's 10 series designed by Kim Albrecht of the project "Artificial Worldviews." The cover features a mapping of over 18,000 synthetically generated data points prompted from ChatGPT on the categories of knowledge.
[src:faker-data/synthetic-data] DataFramer has published datasets on Hugging Face, including *ehr-multi-file-patient-samples*, a synthetic multi-file patient history dataset, and *INSURE-Dial*, a dialogue dataset for insurance-call phase detection and compliance verification.
[src:faker-data/test-data] Test data may be used to verify that a given set of inputs to a function produces an expected result.
[src:faker-data/test-data] Alternatively, data can be used to challenge the program's ability to handle unusual, extreme, exceptional, or unexpected inputs.
[src:faker-data/test-data] Test data can be produced in a focused or systematic manner, as is typically the case in domain testing, or through less focused approaches, such as high-volume randomized automated tests.
[src:faker-data/test-data] Test data can be generated by the tester or by a program or function that assists the tester.
[src:faker-data/test-data] It can be recorded for reuse or used only once.
[src:faker-data/test-data] Test data may be created manually, using data generation tools (often based on randomness), or retrieved from an existing production environment.
[src:faker-data/test-data] The data set may consist of synthetic (fake) data, but ideally, it should include representative (real) data.
[src:faker-data/test-data] Due to privacy regulations such as GDPR, PCI, and the HIPAA, the use of privacy-sensitive personal data for testing is restricted.
[src:faker-data/test-data] However, anonymized (and preferably subsetted) production data may be used as representative data for testing and development.
[src:faker-data/test-data] Programmers may also choose to generate synthetic data as an alternative to using real or anonymized data.
[src:faker-data/test-data] While synthetic data can offer significant advantages, such as enhanced privacy and flexibility, it also comes with limitations.
[src:faker-data/test-data] For instance, generating synthetic data that accurately reflects real-world complexity can be challenging.
[src:faker-data/test-data] There is also a risk of synthetic data not fully capturing the nuances of real data, potentially leading to gaps in test coverage.
[src:faker-data/test-data] Domain testing is a set of techniques focusing on test data.
[src:faker-data/test-data] This includes identifying critical inputs, values at the boundaries between equivalence classes, and combinations of inputs that drive the system toward specific outputs.
[src:faker-data/test-data] Domain testing helps ensure that various scenarios are effectively tested, including edge cases and unusual conditions.
